        <h2 id="examples">Real relevance optimisation examples</h2>

        <h3>Example 1 — Plumber expanding service visibility</h3>
        <p>A plumber with only "Plumbing" listed as a service added four individual service entries to their GBP: "Drain Cleaning," "Water Heater Repair," "Slab Leak Detection," and "Emergency Plumbing." Within 6 weeks, the business appeared in Local Pack results for all four service-specific queries where previously it only appeared for the generic "plumber near me" search.</p>

        <h3>Example 2 — Yoga studio category switch</h3>
        <p>A yoga studio changed its primary GBP category from "Yoga Studio" to "Hot Yoga Studio" — a more specific match for their actual offering. Within 3 weeks they began appearing in Local Pack results for "hot yoga near me" queries, a category they had been invisible in despite being the only hot yoga studio in the area.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — choosing a broad primary category</div>
          <p>Many businesses choose a generic primary category thinking it captures more searches. In practice, "Restaurant" competes with every restaurant in the city; "Thai Restaurant" competes only with Thai restaurants. Specificity wins because the narrower query has clearer intent and weaker relevance competition.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Relevance vs prominence vs distance — which matters most?</h2>
        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Relevance (optimise first)</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Directly controlled through GBP updates</li>
              <li>Fastest ranking lever</li>
              <li>Can overcome distance disadvantage</li>
              <li>Compounded by website + review signals</li>
              <li>Category specificity = competitive edge</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Prominence + Distance (context-dependent)</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Distance is fixed — cannot be changed</li>
              <li>Prominence builds slowly via reviews + links</li>
              <li>Proximity wins for "near me" queries</li>
              <li>High prominence can override distance penalty</li>
              <li>Together they amplify a relevance-optimised profile</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">7 best practices for improving local relevance</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Select the most specific primary category available.</strong> Search GBP category options for the most precise match to your primary service. Update it if Google adds a more specific option later.</li>
          <li><strong>Add all secondary categories that apply.</strong> Secondary categories let you appear in additional search contexts without diluting your primary category signal.</li>
          <li><strong>List every individual service with a description.</strong> Each service entry is separately indexed. Write descriptions that include the exact terms customers search for.</li>
          <li><strong>Rewrite your business description to include service keywords.</strong> Use all 750 characters. Name specific services, specialties, and the areas you serve.</li>
          <li><strong>Build service-specific pages on your website.</strong> Each service should have a dedicated page that reinforces your GBP's claim to that service. Google cross-references your website and your profile.</li>
          <li><strong>Ask customers to mention services in reviews.</strong> Brief, specific review request prompts ("If you're happy to leave a review, mentioning which service we helped with would be great") increase service-specific review content.</li>
          <li><strong>Publish regular GBP posts about specific services.</strong> GBP posts signal active management and reinforce service relevance. Post about seasonal services, promotions, or tips related to your specific offerings.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common relevance mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Keyword stuffing your business name.</strong> Adding keywords to your GBP name ("Joe's Plumbing - Emergency Drain Cleaning Dallas") violates Google's guidelines and risks suspension.</li>
          <li><strong>Using a broad primary category to capture more searches.</strong> Specificity consistently outperforms breadth for service-specific queries.</li>
          <li><strong>Leaving the services section empty.</strong> The services section is one of the most under-used relevance signals. Every listed service is a potential ranking entry point.</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring review content for relevance.</strong> A profile with 200 generic "great service!" reviews has weaker relevance signals than one with 80 reviews that mention specific services by name.</li>
          <li><strong>Mismatching GBP and website content.</strong> If your GBP claims you offer "roof replacement" but your website has no page on that topic, Google sees a signal conflict that reduces confidence in your relevance for that term.</li>
        </ul>

